    "answer_id" : 3980725,
    "question_id" : 3978654,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Depending on what you mean by \"use them as Strings\", you might not want to use an enum here. In most cases, the solution proposed by The Elite Gentleman will allow you to use them through their toString-methods, e.g. in <code>System.out.println(STRING_ONE)</code> or <code>String s = \"Hello \"+STRING_TWO</code>, but when you really need Strings (e.g. <code>STRING_ONE.toLowerCase()</code>), you might prefer defining them as constants:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public interface Strings{\n  public static final String STRING_ONE = \"ONE\";\n  public static final String STRING_TWO = \"TWO\";      \n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
